  "intro": [
    "This lesson connects the two ideas you've met so far: theoretical probability (what the math predicts) and experimental probability (what you actually observe when you run trials). They rarely match exactly, especially in small samples, and that gap is normal random variation \u2014 not a broken coin or a wrong theory.",
    "The key principle is the law of large numbers: as the number of trials grows, the experimental probability tends to settle close to the theoretical value. That's why a larger sample gives a more reliable estimate of the true probability."
  ],
